text.Taxonomy and naming:
The species was first formally described by John McConnell Black in 1928 and the description was published in Transactions and Proceedings of the Royal Society of South Australia. The specific epithet (parvifolia) is derived from the Latin words parvus meaning "small" and folium meaning "leaf", referring to the small leaves of this species.There are two subspecies

Eremophila parvifolia  J.M.Black subsp. parvifolia which is a low, spiny shrub which flowers from June to February and has glabrous, almost spherical fruits ;
Eremophila parvifolia subsp. auricampa Chinnock which is a taller, non-spiny shrub which flowers from September to April and has cone-shaped, hairy fruits.
